ReAct: Synergizing Reasoning and Acting in Language Models
ordered.reason: This paper introduces the ReAct framework, which directly combines reasoning and acting, a core concept for agents performing tasks like information retrieval and verification. It's highly relevant to bridging the gap between an agent's reasoning capabilities and its ability to interact with external tools or environments to achieve a target.

ordered.title: Fact, Fetch, and Reason: A Unified Evaluation of Retrieval-Augmented Generation
ordered.reason: This paper directly addresses 'Fact', 'Fetch', and 'Reason', which are crucial components for a system aiming to extract and verify information. Its focus on Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) is a key paradigm for building such agents.

ordered.title: Scaling Agents via Continual Pre-training
ordered.reason: Scaling agent capabilities through continual pre-training is directly relevant to improving the underlying intelligence of agents that would perform fact extraction and verification. Better foundational models lead to better performance on downstream tasks.

ordered.title: WebWalker: Benchmarking LLMs in Web Traversal
ordered.reason: Web traversal is a fundamental skill for any agent that needs to gather information from the internet. Benchmarking this capability is essential for building effective information retrieval and verification agents.
